vectorData.altText: That's right!  The flexor digitorum superficialis (H) is in the middle layer of the anterior compartment of the arm. Since palmaris longus is absent in this image, the muscle is visible!
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Identify the muscle bellies and tendons of the flexor digitorum superficialis. Follow its tendons to the wrist where they pass deep to the flexor retinaculum, through the carpal tunnel, to the palm of the hand.
GENTLY probe between the tendons of the flexor carpi ulnars and palmaris longus.
You will see this for yourself later in the lab, in a prosected hand as well as in specimens in Grant’s Museum.

Each of the four tendons is distributed to a different finger. As illustrated, each tendon splits to insert onto both sides of the second phalange     . 
Flexor digitorum superficialis flexes the metacarpophalangeal and proximal interphalangeal joints.
